10:35.802 --> 10:42.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a huge investigative
project carried
out by Alexei Navalny's
anti-corruption organization.

10:42.876 --> 10:49.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they put together a story,
and they put
together a film that
demonstrated and meticulously

10:49.949 --> 10:56.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
documented the scale of
corruption on the
part of Russia's prime minister,
Dmitry Medvedev.

10:56.856 --> 11:01.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what was it
about the scale
of corruption?

11:01.094 --> 11:04.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We mentioned some of it, the
houses, the extravagant...

11:04.864 --> 11:11.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASHA GESSEN: The houses, the 50
pairs of
sneakers or however many he
orders every month.

11:11.237 --> 11:14.307 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The -- just, it's obscene.

11:14.340 --> 11:17.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that that's a really
important
aspect of it.

11:17.143 --> 11:19.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not just that he has a lot
of money.

11:19.812 --> 11:23.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's that he behaves obscenely
with that amount
of money.

11:23.683 --> 11:26.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It is sort of -- it is
unimaginable.

11:26.119 --> 11:30.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is unimaginable indecency.

11:30.390 --> 11:32.158 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it has been made public.

11:32.191 --> 11:37.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Given the level
of repression
in Russia, Masha Gessen, what do
protesters

11:37.597 --> 11:39.532 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
think they can accomplish?

11:39.566 --> 11:46.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASHA GESSEN: I don't think
these are protesters
who have a specific goal in
mind, as in, we're

11:46.105 --> 11:49.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to come out into the
streets and get
this done.

11:49.309 --> 11:55.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that, again, these are
very young
people, so they may not be fully
aware of

11:55.381 --> 11:57.483 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the threat that they are facing.

11:57.517 --> 12:03.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The last protests in Russia five
years ago
ended in a massive crackdown and
in dozens

12:03.489 --> 12:07.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
arrests of peaceful
demonstrators who went
to prison for years at a time.

12:07.627 --> 12:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it's likely that the
same fate
will face these young people.

12:12.999 --> 12:19.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think they may even need a
greater crackdown
to put an end to these protests,
because these

12:19.339 --> 12:24.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are young people who don't watch
television
and who won't be quite as afraid
of jail,

12:24.110 --> 12:26.279 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
just because they are so young.

12:26.312 --> 12:32.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what I really fear is, if
these protests
continue, is the kind of
violence in the streets

12:32.218 --> 12:33.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that we haven't seen before in
Russia.

12:33.886 --> 12:37.323 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You have
mentioned a couple
of times the threat that they
face.

12:37.357 --> 12:39.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, how real is the threat?

12:39.058 --> 12:42.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What could happen to these
people if they
continue to come out in the
streets?

12:42.862 --> 12:49.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASHA GESSEN: Well, what has
happened to protesters
in the past was that, basically,
the government

12:49.769 --> 12:56.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 2012 put an end to a series
of mass protests
by changing laws, by making it
possible to

12:56.275 --> 13:03.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
arrest anybody for protests, and
by making
basically a show of imprisoning
not just protest

13:03.416 --> 13:09.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leaders, and not specifically
protest leaders,
but activists, rank-and-file
protest participants.

13:09.489 --> 13:16.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That gets across the idea that
anybody who
joins a protest without being an
organizer,

13:16.195 --> 13:21.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
without being a visible leader,
risks arrest,
and not risks just arrest, but
years in a

13:21.834 --> 13:23.670 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Russian jail.

13:23.703 --> 13:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And do you see
anything changing
about this regime as a result of
this level

13:27.874 --> 13:33.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of public distrust of this
government?

13:33.713 --> 13:37.016 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MASHA GESSEN: Well, yes and no.

13:37.050 --> 13:42.221 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They're -- I mean, these
protesters came out
against corruption, which is a
little bit

13:42.255 --> 13:47.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
different from coming out
against -- politically
against this regime.

13:47.460 --> 13:50.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Importantly, they were not
protesting the
war in Ukraine.

13:50.763 --> 13:53.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were not protesting the
murder of opposition
leaders.

13:53.733 --> 13:55.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They were protesting corruption.

13:55.501 --> 14:01.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That does give the government an
opportunity
to take anti-corruption
measures, to fire

14:01.074 --> 14:06.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Medvedev, to fire somebody else
who can be
accused of corruption, to make a
show of fighting

14:06.713 --> 14:07.680 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
corruption.

14:07.714 --> 14:09.449 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

14:09.482 --> 14:13.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think these protesters at this
point are
stopping a little bit short of
demanding an

14:13.953 --> 14:17.857 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
end to the Putin regime.

14:17.890 --> 14:21.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their demands are not explicitly
political
nature.

14:21.694 --> 14:24.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are really demanding good
government.

14:24.630 --> 14:25.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But that could change.

14:26.032 --> 14:29.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Masha Gessen,
journalist and
author, we thank you.

14:29.635 --> 14:33.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MASHA GESSEN: Thank you.

14:33.406 --> 14:43.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: A bombing in
Iraq by the
American-led military coalition
leaves scores

14:43.449 --> 14:48.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: A bombing in
Iraq by the
American-led military coalition
leaves scores

14:48.554 --> 14:49.522 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
dead.

14:49.555 --> 14:51.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has that.

14:51.390 --> 14:56.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The airstrike took
place in the
Al Jadida neighborhood of
Western Mosul amid

14:56.229 --> 15:00.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pitched fighting between ISIS
militants and
Iraqi government forces.

15:00.533 --> 15:05.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The reports from the scene are
gruesome, more
than 100 dead.

15:05.271 --> 15:09.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on this incident and
the brutal battle
there, I'm joined from Irbil in
Northern Iraq

15:09.842 --> 15:13.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
via Skype by Loveday Morris of
The Washington
Post.

15:13.513 --> 15:15.047 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Loveday, thanks for joining us.

15:15.081 --> 15:17.150 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I know it's very late there.

15:17.183 --> 15:19.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been 10 days since this
incident took
place.

15:19.986 --> 15:24.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Pentagon said the air
assault took place
on March 17.

15:24.290 --> 15:26.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do we know about what
happened?

15:26.626 --> 15:30.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS, The Washington
Post: What
happened was, Iraqi forces were
advancing

15:30.229 --> 15:36.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the area at the time with
an ISIS-held
area.

15:36.169 --> 15:40.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was one where residents say
that there
were a lot of ISIS fighters
fighting from

15:40.473 --> 15:44.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the rooftops, and they were
sheltering in
their homes.

15:44.744 --> 15:49.715 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And as the Iraqi forces
advanced, there was
heavy bombardment on this
neighborhood.

15:49.749 --> 15:56.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are allegations of
actually multiple
buildings hit by U.S.
airstrikes, but that

15:56.956 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one particular building where
they have pulled
out more than 100 bodies, 101
bodies now,

16:03.563 --> 16:06.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and that's an alleged site of
one of the strikes.

16:06.966 --> 16:09.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But the Iraqis are
saying that
it was booby-trapped by ISIS.

16:09.802 --> 16:11.737 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS: Yes, that's
right.

16:11.771 --> 16:17.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They said they have made an
initial investigation,
and this particular building was
booby-trapped

16:17.343 --> 16:18.678 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
by ISIS.

16:18.711 --> 16:22.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Initially, commanders blamed it
on an ISIS
car bomb, the collapse.

16:22.849 --> 16:26.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There have been several
conflicting stories.

16:26.385 --> 16:31.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraqi civil defense, the rescue
workers who
are pulling the bodies out of
the building,

16:31.657 --> 16:36.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they say they're experts in
building collapses,
and they say this was caused by
an airstrikes.

16:36.796 --> 16:42.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the U.S. coalition has said
that it carried
out a strike at the location of
accusations

16:42.635 --> 16:44.604 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of mass civilian casualties.

16:44.637 --> 16:50.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: We have seen this
fighting around
Mosul really intensify.

16:50.042 --> 16:54.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Trump had said he
wanted give commanders
in the field more flexibility.

16:54.280 --> 16:58.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do we know about the rules
covering airstrikes
like these?

16:58.584 --> 17:00.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Have they changed since
President Trump came
into office?

17:00.953 --> 17:05.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS: What we hear on
the U.S. side
and from the coalition is, no,
there's been

17:05.691 --> 17:09.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no change at all for the rules
of engagement
so far.

17:09.295 --> 17:10.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Iraqis are saying that as
well.

17:10.930 --> 17:13.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Official, there's no change to
the rules of
engagement.

17:13.232 --> 17:16.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There does seem to be some
speeding of the
process of calling in
airstrikes.

17:16.936 --> 17:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have made the process
faster.

17:18.905 --> 17:24.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have put U.S. forward air
controllers
closer to Mosul.

17:24.777 --> 17:29.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's really unclear what
exactly is causing
this.

17:29.315 --> 17:34.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there has been a spike now
in civilian
casualty accusations both in
Iraq and Syria.

17:34.387 --> 17:40.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And this is in Mosul,
some of the
most intense urban fighting,
street-to-street,

17:40.426 --> 17:41.427 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
house-to-house.

17:41.460 --> 17:43.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the impact on the
civilian population?

17:43.429 --> 17:45.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS: It's a huge
impact.

17:45.197 --> 17:49.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have a huge amount of
ordnance flying
into that city, not just from
airstrikes,

17:50.002 --> 17:51.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but from artillery.

17:51.304 --> 17:54.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, obviously, ISIS also uses
heavy weaponry
and booby-traps.

17:54.807 --> 18:01.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Really, you talk to civilians
that are coming
out of Mosul, they have been in
their basements

18:01.147 --> 18:02.448 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for weeks on end.

18:02.481 --> 18:03.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're absolutely terrified.

18:04.016 --> 18:09.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ISIS are using their rooftops
and make them
keep their front doors open.

18:09.755 --> 18:16.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they're very scared of
airstrikes on their
own houses while they're hiding
inside.

18:16.095 --> 18:19.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People are coming out, and, yes,
a horrific
state.

18:19.732 --> 18:22.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's very little food, water
inside.

18:22.301 --> 18:23.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The area is under siege.

18:23.302 --> 18:25.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a terrible situation for
civilians.

18:25.171 --> 18:26.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Are they able to
flee?

18:26.172 --> 18:27.306 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS: Some are.

18:27.340 --> 18:29.041 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Some aren't.

18:29.075 --> 18:33.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, they normally can't flee
until the
Iraqi security forces get to
their area.

18:33.879 --> 18:41.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What has happened, in some
cases, ISIS will
send a wave of civilians out.

18:41.387 --> 18:43.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They will order them to leave
their homes.

18:43.723 --> 18:47.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Iraqis will have to hold
fire if there's
a big wave of civilians coming
out.

18:47.893 --> 18:49.695 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It really slows them down.

18:49.729 --> 18:53.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, sometimes, people come out
like that.

18:53.099 --> 18:58.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other times, ISIS keep them in,
keeps them
blocked in their neighborhood to
use as human

18:58.304 --> 19:00.106 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
shields.

19:00.139 --> 19:05.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in that case, I mean, any
time people
are coming out, they're always
caught in very

19:05.077 --> 19:06.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dangerous crossfire.

19:06.078 --> 19:07.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have snipers.

19:07.079 --> 19:08.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have mortars.

19:08.214 --> 19:12.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, it's tough for people to
get out, for
sure.

19:12.385 --> 19:18.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Loveday Morris, The
Washington
Post, from Irbil, thanks for
joining us, and

19:18.557 --> 19:20.893 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
be safe.

19:20.926 --> 19:25.631 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LOVEDAY MORRIS: Thank you.

19:25.664 --> 19:28.868 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

19:28.901 --> 19:34.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
