reasonable
for me to be able to afford
insurance.

20:52.952 --> 20:57.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The health care act came up, and
although
the first time when I applied, I
was able

20:57.289 --> 21:01.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to get subsidies, when I filed
taxes at the
end of the year, they ended up
telling me

21:01.293 --> 21:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, as a matter of fact, I
shouldn't have
been able to get subsidies, and
I had to pay

21:04.497 --> 21:06.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all of them back.

21:06.465 --> 21:09.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Moving forward, from that point
on, I was
really not in a position to be
able to afford

21:09.768 --> 21:11.370 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
health insurance anymore.

21:11.403 --> 21:16.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If I had chosen to get
insurance, the cost
of living for me would've
changed.

21:16.675 --> 21:21.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My grocery bills, I wouldn't be
able to afford,
my gas, my mortgage.

21:21.514 --> 21:24.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It really would take a toll on
everything.

21:24.650 --> 21:26.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I definitely do worry about not
having insurance.

21:27.019 --> 21:28.554 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's a lot of what-ifs.

21:28.587 --> 21:32.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even last year, I took a tumble
down the stairs
and ended up in an InstaCare.

21:32.758 --> 21:34.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there's just a lot of
worries that go
with that.

21:34.960 --> 21:37.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN GARRETT, Salt Lake City:
I'm John Garrett.

21:37.563 --> 21:42.835 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm 24 years old, and I am a
front desk associate
here at Camp Bow Wow.

21:42.868 --> 21:47.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not very worried about not
having health
insurance at the moment, because
I'm pretty

21:47.239 --> 21:50.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
young, and I don't have that
much going on
with me.

21:50.442 --> 21:54.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if I can, you know, afford to
skip that
bill and save that, that much
money a month,

21:54.246 --> 21:56.982 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I definitely would prefer to do
that.

21:57.016 --> 22:00.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We did have to pay a penalty for
not having
health insurance.

22:00.619 --> 22:02.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the first year, it was about
$200.

22:02.788 --> 22:07.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that wasn't a big deal at
the time.

22:07.560 --> 22:10.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The next year, I think it was
double, about
$400, and then the year after
that, it was

22:10.563 --> 22:12.298 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
$700.

22:12.331 --> 22:14.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATRICIA SMITH: I think it's a
little silly
for me to have to pay for
something that I

22:14.166 --> 22:16.936 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
simply can't afford anyways.

22:16.969 --> 22:21.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Moving forward, if the law is
supposed to
change and we're able to afford
health insurance

22:21.040 --> 22:25.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and we were able to get money
back and things
like that to pay for it, I would
love to put

22:25.277 --> 22:28.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
money in health insurance, so
that I don't
have to have the worry that I
have right now.

22:28.214 --> 22:32.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: At the same
time, there are
concerns about out-of- pocket
costs.

22:32.117 --> 22:36.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's meet a woman in Ohio who
has a chronic
health problem and is grateful
for the coverage

22:36.622 --> 22:39.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
she receives through the
Affordable Care Act.

22:39.225 --> 22:43.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was politically active in
opposing the
Republican bill, but says even
the current

22:43.529 --> 22:44.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
law could be improved.

22:44.697 --> 22:47.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MINDY HEDGES, Radnor, Ohio: My
name is Mindy
Hedges.

22:47.666 --> 22:51.437 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I live in Radnor, Ohio, Delaware
County.

22:51.470 --> 22:53.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And my age is 61.

22:53.772 --> 22:56.275 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Well, I'm a type 1 diabetic.

22:56.308 --> 23:00.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have been a type 1 diabetic
since the age
of 5.

23:00.713 --> 23:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That means a lot of medication.

23:03.282 --> 23:07.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I test myself, my blood
sugar, about six
to eight times a day.

23:08.020 --> 23:11.457 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is a lot of medicines that I
need to take.

23:11.490 --> 23:14.059 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm on an insulin pump, very
expensive.

23:14.093 --> 23:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My pharmaceuticals are about
$1,200 a month.

23:18.731 --> 23:24.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had a -- my own company for 18
years, and
the recession hit and the
business closed.

23:25.004 --> 23:27.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I tried to get insurance and
couldn't.

23:27.906 --> 23:33.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nobody would cover me because I
have a preexisting
condition.

23:33.512 --> 23:39.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And of the company that I talked
to me at
all about how much it would
cost, it was between

23:39.251 --> 23:41.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
$2,500 to $5,000.

23:41.320 --> 23:44.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And even at that, they also
wouldn't cover
me

23:44.156 --> 23:52.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I was begging for -- people
were giving
me supplies.

23:52.498 --> 23:58.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had a friend that worked in
the medical
field that was giving me insulin
and syringes.

23:58.704 --> 24:02.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: All these coverages just
wouldn't cover
me.

24:02.241 --> 24:07.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MINDY HEDGES: I was waiting for
the Affordable
Care Act to come into to get
passed.

24:07.946 --> 24:09.315 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Finally, it did.

24:09.348 --> 24:10.716 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I was so thankful.

24:10.749 --> 24:15.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We pay a substantial amount, but
I still get
a subsidy for it.

24:15.854 --> 24:20.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, my payment right now is $445
a month.

24:20.693 --> 24:24.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's not a system that --
that is that
is pure.

24:24.530 --> 24:29.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm sure that it has some
things that
need to be fixed.

24:29.101 --> 24:36.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if only we could just fix
them, instead
of coming up with something that
is so totally

24:36.041 --> 24:37.643 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
broken.

24:37.676 --> 24:40.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's a
sampling of the
concerns we heard across the
country.

24:40.145 --> 24:44.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's get our hands around what
exactly will
happen now with health care.

24:44.717 --> 24:48.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Problems remain, but how will
insurers and
all of us handle them?

24:48.454 --> 24:53.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mary Agnes Carey of Kaiser
Health News is
here to walk through some of
these issues.

24:53.058 --> 24:54.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thank you for joining us, Mary
Agnes.

24:54.326 --> 24:55.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY, Kaiser Health
News: Thanks
for having me.

24:55.861 --> 24:57.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Let's start
with something
President Trump said on Friday.

24:57.696 --> 24:59.531 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Listen.

24:59.565 --> 25:04.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
I have been saying for the last
year-and-a-half

25:04.370 --> 25:09.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the best thing we can do,
politically
speaking, is let Obamacare
explode.

25:09.375 --> 25:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is exploding right now.

25:12.811 --> 25:15.581 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Many states have big problems.

25:15.614 --> 25:17.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Almost all states have big
problems.

25:17.483 --> 25:20.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Now, it's
obviously a piece
of rhetoric, but it is certainly
echoed around

25:20.486 --> 25:21.620 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Washington.

25:21.653 --> 25:24.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will just ask you right away:
Will Obamacare
explode?

25:24.857 --> 25:26.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that accurate?

25:26.425 --> 25:29.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And regardless of the answer of
at the question,
where are the real problems now?

25:29.361 --> 25:30.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: I don't think
it will explode.

25:30.896 --> 25:33.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There are definitely some
problems with affordability.

25:33.165 --> 25:37.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You mentioned that average 25
percent increase
in the federal exchanges.

25:37.102 --> 25:39.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Rural areas, the prices tend to
be higher.

25:39.671 --> 25:41.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Urban areas, the prices tend to
be lower.

25:41.974 --> 25:44.376 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it really depends on where
you live.

25:44.410 --> 25:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are insurers getting into that
market?

25:46.345 --> 25:50.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How much competition is there
between the
doctors and the hospitals, that
sort of thing,

25:50.315 --> 25:52.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with the providers in the
marketplace?

25:52.084 --> 25:53.352 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But there's a lot of variance.

25:53.385 --> 25:55.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let me give you an example.

25:55.187 --> 25:59.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For this year, in 2017, for one
of the plans
offered on the exchange, for a
40-year-old

25:59.525 --> 26:04.163 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
nonsmoker in Louisville,
Kentucky, it was
$229 a month.

26:04.196 --> 26:09.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That same premium in Anchorage,
Alaska, was
$904, but this is before the
subsidies that

26:09.535 --> 26:12.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
help eight in 10 people in the
exchanges lower
that price.

26:12.438 --> 26:15.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And so it seems
that rural
areas, Anchorage might be an
example, those

26:15.574 --> 26:18.043 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are the ones where see the
biggest problems.

26:18.076 --> 26:22.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, Congress, it seems, is not
planning to
do anything to repair the
system, at least

26:22.414 --> 26:23.415 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the foreseeable future.

26:23.449 --> 26:24.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But insurers have no choice.

26:24.616 --> 26:25.784 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have to take action.

26:25.818 --> 26:28.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are the decisions facing
insurers coming
up soon?

26:28.821 --> 26:30.589 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Sure.

26:30.622 --> 26:34.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have to decide by June --
it was May,
but the administration moved it
back because

26:34.059 --> 26:37.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of all the uncertainty over the
health care
debate we have both been
covering on Capitol

26:37.696 --> 26:39.531 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Hill.

26:39.565 --> 26:42.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, by May, they need to get --
by June, rather,
they need to get in their
premium estimates.

26:42.401 --> 26:45.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they will be looking at
their experience
in the market.

26:45.070 --> 26:46.438 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Who are they covering?

26:46.472 --> 26:48.106 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How sick have these people been?

26:48.140 --> 26:50.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We know that the sickest folks
came in first.

26:50.375 --> 26:52.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're very, very expensive.

26:52.444 --> 26:56.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some have thought that 25
percent premium
jump is going to be sort of a
one-time anomaly.

26:56.815 --> 26:59.084 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Will that even out for 2018?

26:59.117 --> 27:00.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What's the competition in the
marketplace?

27:00.853 --> 27:05.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are other insurers there looking
at their
risk pool, all the people
they're insuring?

27:05.557 --> 27:08.460 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're trying to get a full
look everything.

27:08.494 --> 27:11.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they will also be wondering
if the Trump
administration will enforce this
thing called

27:11.997 --> 27:13.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the individual mandate.

27:13.799 --> 27:17.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a requirement that most
Americans
have coverage or pay a fine.

27:17.202 --> 27:20.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Insurers like it because it
makes the healthy
and the sicker people get in.

27:20.672 --> 27:22.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Like the
younger people that
we heard mentioned in the piece.

27:22.975 --> 27:24.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Exactly.

27:24.743 --> 27:25.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That was
obviously something
they were thinking about, that
penalty.

27:25.310 --> 27:27.145 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Right.

27:27.179 --> 27:29.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: The question is
whether the
Trump administration will
actually force them

27:29.181 --> 27:30.649 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to pay it.

27:30.682 --> 27:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Right, because
the younger
people tend to be healthier.

27:32.584 --> 27:36.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the more of those folks that
are in the
risk pool, the better off, the
lower the premiums,

27:36.688 --> 27:38.590 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
usually.

27:38.624 --> 27:39.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: All right,
Republicans still
have the health and human
services secretary,

27:40.025 --> 27:41.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Tom Price.

27:41.226 --> 27:42.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What power does he have?

27:42.995 --> 27:45.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Or Hollywood decisions is he
thinking about
right now when it comes to the
Affordable

27:45.631 --> 27:47.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Care Act and our health care
system?

27:47.132 --> 27:48.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: Sure.

27:48.133 --> 27:49.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He could do some things
administratively.

27:49.968 --> 27:53.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have to remember the
Affordable Care Act
gives the health and human
services secretary

27:53.572 --> 27:55.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lots and lots of power.

27:55.474 --> 27:59.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He could examine these things
called the essential
health benefits, those 10
categories that

27:59.378 --> 28:05.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
include maternity care,
emergency services,
mental health services, and
perhaps give insurers

28:05.250 --> 28:09.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a little more flexibility over
whether or
not they have to offer those.

28:09.154 --> 28:15.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you talk about the Medicaid
program,
they may be a lot more open to
new approaches

28:15.294 --> 28:19.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from states, including work
requirements for
the Medicaid beneficiaries.

28:19.531 --> 28:23.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And back to the Affordable Care
Act, there
is this other area of subsidies.

28:23.402 --> 28:24.403 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's premium subsidies.

28:24.436 --> 28:26.338 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's cost-sharing subsidies.

28:26.371 --> 28:30.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're part of a legal battle,
but the bottom
line is, the Trump
administration and Republicans

28:30.108 --> 28:33.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Congress could decide not to
fund these.

28:33.211 --> 28:36.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
About 60 percent of people who
get help on
the exchanges get the
cost-sharing.

28:36.982 --> 28:40.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They help with the co-pays and
other out-of-pocket
deductibles.

28:40.419 --> 28:43.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if they did, they would have
quite a problem
with the insurers.

28:43.155 --> 28:45.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And so to be
clear now, that
is not the general subsidies
people get to

28:45.924 --> 28:46.892 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
get insurance.

28:46.925 --> 28:48.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARY AGNES CAREY: no.

28:48.794 --> 28:49.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That is help
for people to
pay when you get to the doctor,
your deductible

28:49.962 --> 28:51.029 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and all of that.

28:51.063 --> 28:52.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: That's right,
your out-of-pocket.

28:52.664 --> 28:55.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: And the
Republicans could
decide not to provide that
money.

28:55.033 --> 28:58.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Insurers are worried, if
Republicans don't,
then they are going to have
people who don't

28:58.804 --> 28:59.771 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pay.

28:59.805 --> 29:00.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

29:00.806 --> 29:02.074 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARY AGNES CAREY: That's right.

