47:54.705 --> 47:55.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks for having me.

47:55.873 --> 47:57.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I wasn't sure
what I was opening
up.

47:57.141 --> 47:59.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I expected to see something
about the Bible
and archaeology.

47:59.810 --> 48:01.345 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I did.

48:01.378 --> 48:05.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But you also write about
yourself, about relationships,
about modern technology.

48:05.249 --> 48:06.851 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What were you after in looking
at their story?

48:06.884 --> 48:10.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: What happened to
me was, we
were on a trip to Rome as a
family.

48:10.921 --> 48:13.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we -- I took my daughters
into the Sistine
Chapel.

48:13.491 --> 48:14.458 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I'm like, listen up, girls.

48:14.492 --> 48:15.793 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm going to blow your mind.

48:15.826 --> 48:17.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

48:17.595 --> 48:19.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: And one of them
looks up and
sees Adam and God sailing across
the skies.

48:19.463 --> 48:21.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The famous moment
where they're
touching.

48:21.265 --> 48:25.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: The famous moment,
and says,
well, you know, where am I in
that picture,

48:25.202 --> 48:26.337 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

48:26.370 --> 48:28.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is from the point of view
of an 8-year-old
girl.

48:28.105 --> 48:32.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And her sister points out
something I had
never seen before, which is Eve
underneath

48:32.376 --> 48:33.410 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
God's arm.

48:33.444 --> 48:35.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she says, you know, is that
Eve?

48:35.346 --> 48:37.081 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's just when it hit me.

48:37.114 --> 48:40.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I realized, for 3,000 years,
this story
has been at the heart of every
conversation

48:40.918 --> 48:42.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about men, women and sex.

48:42.419 --> 48:46.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if I wanted to understand
today, maybe
I needed to understand them.

48:46.257 --> 48:51.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as absurd as it sounds, I
asked myself,
might Adam and Eve be the role
models that

48:51.395 --> 48:53.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we are looking for?

48:53.197 --> 48:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so, OK,
before we -- go
back to the original Adam and
Eve, because

48:55.866 --> 48:56.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you had to, right?

48:56.867 --> 48:57.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRUCE FEILER: Yes.

48:57.868 --> 48:59.236 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Yes, exactly.

48:59.270 --> 49:03.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have got the original story
that appears
in the text in Genesis.

49:03.207 --> 49:09.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then what you have is
organized religion
sort of glomming onto the story
and entirely

49:09.547 --> 49:10.514 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reinterpreting it.

49:10.548 --> 49:12.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And by organized religion, I
mean men.

49:12.483 --> 49:16.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that what you have
here is a situation
where Adam and Eve, but
especially Eve, are

49:16.520 --> 49:21.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
victims of the greatest
character assassination
the world has ever known.

49:21.458 --> 49:27.364 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Basically, the story was
weaponized as a way
to elevate men and to hurt
women.

49:27.398 --> 49:30.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you go back to the story,
that's not what
you find.

49:30.067 --> 49:32.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I mean, I think the first
thing, just
to sort of set the stage briefly
here, is,

49:33.003 --> 49:34.071 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you have got two stories.

49:34.104 --> 49:36.607 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The second story is more famous,
right?

49:36.640 --> 49:40.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's -- you have got Adam
being created
from the earth, Eve being
created Adam, the

49:40.611 --> 49:42.580 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fruit and getting kicked out of
Eden.

49:42.613 --> 49:47.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the first story is very
different, because,
in the first story, you have got
man and woman

49:47.418 --> 49:49.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
being created in the image of
God.

49:49.587 --> 49:51.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What's true for one is true for
the other.

49:51.455 --> 49:54.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The whole story begins in
equality.

49:54.491 --> 49:56.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's what got lost in all
these interpretations.

49:56.327 --> 50:00.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of the
central tenets of
your book is that humans were
meant to be

50:00.064 --> 50:01.031 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
together, right?

50:01.065 --> 50:02.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRUCE FEILER: Yes.

50:02.266 --> 50:04.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But this is a
model for looking
at love.

50:04.201 --> 50:08.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Give me an example for our
audience to understand
what it is you're -- how you're
bringing their

50:08.205 --> 50:10.007 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
story up to our own time.

50:10.040 --> 50:13.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: In every other
story that comes
before, you have got a God, and
a God creating

50:13.811 --> 50:15.779 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
humans, or a God and a human.

50:15.813 --> 50:18.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The biblical story represents a
revolution
in thought.

50:18.482 --> 50:21.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the first story that has a
man and woman
at the start of the human line.

50:21.952 --> 50:25.122 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have to succeed in order
for us to succeed.

50:25.155 --> 50:26.457 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, why are they a model?

50:26.490 --> 50:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because, look, they begin
together, and then
Eve grows Bored.

50:29.927 --> 50:30.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She wants autonomy.

50:30.928 --> 50:31.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She wants independence.

50:31.929 --> 50:32.997 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She goes and she eats the fruit.

50:33.030 --> 50:33.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
She comes back.

50:34.031 --> 50:35.799 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She gives Adam a choice.

50:35.833 --> 50:37.968 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he has to decide, what do I
do?

50:38.002 --> 50:38.969 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He chooses her.

50:39.003 --> 50:39.937 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They leave Eden.

50:39.970 --> 50:40.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They could separate.

50:40.971 --> 50:42.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They stay together and have
children.

50:42.072 --> 50:43.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
One of them murders the other.

50:43.741 --> 50:45.576 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They reconcile and have a third.

50:45.609 --> 50:48.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of my
colleagues was looking
at the book today, and he said
-- and I said

50:48.612 --> 50:49.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what I was doing.

50:49.880 --> 50:51.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he said, you know, this
story doesn't
end well, right?

50:51.949 --> 50:52.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's the fall.

50:52.950 --> 50:54.585 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's the banishment.

50:54.618 --> 50:55.586 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's all this trouble.

50:55.619 --> 50:57.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How is that a model?

50:57.288 --> 51:00.090 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRUCE FEILER: It ends
brilliantly, because
most people think it ends in
Eden.

51:00.124 --> 51:01.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No, they have -- they become
parents.

51:02.026 --> 51:04.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't go well with Cain and
Abel.

51:04.428 --> 51:06.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That could be the end of the
story.

51:06.163 --> 51:07.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They reconcile, have a third
child.

51:07.765 --> 51:08.732 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's incredibly inspirational.

51:08.766 --> 51:10.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, what I think the lessons
are?

51:10.100 --> 51:13.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Number one, constancy,
stick-to-itiveness,
right?

51:13.237 --> 51:17.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The modern psychologists tell us
that you
have to mend relationships.

51:17.107 --> 51:18.375 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the most important thing.

51:18.409 --> 51:20.110 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK?

51:20.144 --> 51:23.113 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Then there's also this
incredible balance
in the story, this mix of
independence and

51:23.147 --> 51:24.915 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
interdependence.

51:24.949 --> 51:29.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's incredibly powerful today
that didn't
happen again until we
re-equalized Eve in

51:29.086 --> 51:30.955 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the last couple of decades.

51:30.988 --> 51:33.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, to me, the biggest idea
that I have learned
-- I basically went in to write
a book about

51:33.857 --> 51:36.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Adam and Eve, ended up writing a
book about
love.

51:36.226 --> 51:37.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And what did I learn?

51:37.428 --> 51:39.730 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Love is a story you tell with
another person.

51:39.763 --> 51:40.731 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

51:40.764 --> 51:42.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's co-creation through
co-narration.

51:42.232 --> 51:44.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's what Adam and Eve
embody.

51:44.702 --> 51:47.504 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what do we learn from them?

51:47.538 --> 51:51.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you hit a bump in the road,
you have
a rupture, you add a new chapter
to your story.

51:51.909 --> 51:57.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the first to tell a
story together
and to recognize you need both.

51:57.982 --> 52:00.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Theirs is the first joint
byline.

52:00.651 --> 52:02.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's a very powerful
lesson for today.

52:02.686 --> 52:06.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The question you
ask here is,
can Adam and Eve be role models
for relationships

52:06.824 --> 52:07.791 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today?

52:07.825 --> 52:09.059 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the answer, apparently, is
yes.

52:09.093 --> 52:11.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: I believe deeply
and profoundly.

52:11.295 --> 52:13.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And more than that, I think that
we need the
story to work.

52:14.031 --> 52:18.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
At this moment, when
relationships are commodities,
and we let each other down, and
our society

52:18.102 --> 52:21.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is being frayed -- we all know
that -- we
need our first story to be one
of success.

52:21.672 --> 52:26.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, essentially, what I'm saying
to people
is, if you care about men and
women and their

52:26.510 --> 52:29.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relationship, if you want to
strengthen and
deepen your own relationship, if
you're interested

52:29.947 --> 52:32.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in love or religion, come on
this journey.

52:32.049 --> 52:34.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, as you have said here,
you will be
surprised.

52:34.318 --> 52:35.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You will learn something.

52:35.853 --> 52:39.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in the end, I think you
will be uplifted,
because this story works.

52:39.256 --> 52:42.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, today, we need stories that
work at the
heart of our culture.

52:42.626 --> 52:46.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The book is "The
First Love
Story: Adam, Eve, and Us."

52:46.063 --> 52:48.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bruce Feiler, thank you very
much.

52:48.065 --> 52:53.437 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRUCE FEILER: It's an honor.

